Credit Card Transactions Project¶

Author: Sixian Chen

The Office of Management and Enterprise Services in the State of Oklahoma has made its purchase credit card transactions available. This dataset contains information on purchases made through the purchase card programs administered by the state and higher education institutions.

The purpose of this project is to create various features from raw dataset and detect fraudulent credit card transactions using these features.

Your can download data from here.

Remove negative transactions¶

The original dataset contains transactions with negative amounts. This happens when a cardholder purchased an item (an expense transaction) but then receive his money back. Since our object is to detect fraud transactions, we will remove these negative transactions from our dataset.

In [5]:
df[df['Amount']<0].shape # We have 14531 transactions with negative amounts.
Out[5]:
(14531, 15)
In [6]:
df = df[df['Amount']>0]

Section 3 Feature Engineering ¶

Back to Table of Contents

Instructions:

  • Understand the data grain: each row is a cardholder (last name + first name)

  • An agency can have multiple cardholders. A corporate card (agency_name) can be used by many cardholders and these cardholders have to follow the corporation policy.

  • Intuition: One or two cardholders may abuse their corporate cards. If we compare a cardholder to his agency, we can find outliers.

  • The spending for a merchant category can be higher than others. It does not make sense to compare the spending of a merchant category to another. An agency can spend on various merchant categories, and you cannot claim anomalies just because the spending on one merchant category is higher than another.

  • Anomaly detection is about "comparing a transaction to a benchmark". What is the right benchmark?

  • So we will aggregate to the Aggrecy_Name level and card holder level then build features.

  • Common sense tells us the comparison should be at "Agency_Name" and "Merchant_Category" level.

  • We need to create features for both training set and test set.

Back to Table of Contents

My thought process:

  • The benchmark of this feature is the average amount of trasaction.

  • We can compare each transaction's amount to the average amount of transaction at "Agency_Name" and "Merchant_Category" level.

Back to Table of Contents

My thought process:

  • We know a fraud transaction would have a relatively high amount of spending in a certain time interval. Therefore, we can compare the amount of each transaction to the average spending of that month to detect anomaly.

  • Also, the comparison here happened at "Agency_Name" and "Merchant_Category" level.

3.5 Feature 5: The ratio to average amount spending of day of week ¶

Back to Table of Contents

My thought process:

  • If a credit card was compromised, we can assume that amount of transaction in a particular day can be extremely high.

  • Therefore, we can compare each transaction's amount to the average amount of each day in a week. For example, if a transaction happened at Monday, we can compare its amount to the average Monday transaction amount. By choosing day of week as a benchmark, we are able to detect anomalies.

3.6 Feature 6: The ratio to Average amount spent per day over the past 30 days ¶

Back to Table of Contents

Thought process:

  • The intuition here is that because one person's behavior might change along with time, latest 30 days transactions are more important than previous several months transactions. A latest transaction could reflect a cardholder's behavior more accurately.

  • By comparing transaction amount to the averaged amount in the past 30 days, we are able to detect anomalies.

  • On "Agency_name" and "merchant_category" level, we compare each transaction's amount to the average amount spent per day over the past 30 days.

3.8 Feature 8: The ratio to number of transactions by month ¶

Back to Table of Contents

My thought process:

  • Because a fraudster want to exploit a credit card in a time period before the card is cancelled. If a credit card is compromised, the number of transaction of a fraudster would be extremely high compared to a normal cardholder's number of transactions.

  • Therefore, we can compare each cardholder's total number of transactions on montly basis to the average number of transactions in that month. In this way, by choosing the average number of transactions as a benchmark, we are able to identify abnormal credit card usage.

  • Remember, a cardholder with high number of transactions in one day cannot be viewed as anomly, we have to compare the a card holder's total number of transactions to the monthly average number of transactions in "Agency_Name" and "Merchant_category" level.

First, to get the averaged result, we need to calculate the total number of transactions in each month.

In [45]:
# Calculate total number of transactions group by agency, merchant category, and month

stat_by_month = pd.DataFrame(stat_by_month)
stat_by_month.columns = ['Total_count']

Next, we calculate the number of card holders in each month.

To identify each cardholder, we create a new variable called 'Full_Name' by combining a card holder's first name and last name.

People have the same name could influence our aggregated result. This problem can be solved if the credit card company could provide us with unique identifier of each card.

To simplfy the problem, we do not consider the possibility of two people have the same name.

3.11 Feature 11: The ratio to average number of transactions during the past 30 days ¶

Back to Table of Contents

My thought process:

  • Because a fraudster want to exploit a credit card in a very short time period before the card is cancelled. If a credit card is compromised, the number of transaction of a fraudster would be extremely high compared to a normal cardholder's average number of transactions.

  • Therefore, we can compare each cardholder's average number of transactions in the past 30 days to the average number of transactions over all cardholders during the past 30 days. In this way, we can identify abnormal credit card usage.

  • Remember, a cardholder with high number of transactions in one day cannot be viewed as anomly, we have to compare the number to the average number of transactions at "Agency_Name" and "Merchant_category" level.

First, to get the averaged result, we need to calculate the total number of transactions for every transaction date.

In [61]:
# Calculate the total number of transactions at agency and merchant level for every transaction date.
z = train.groupby(['Agency_Name','Merchant_Category','Transaction_Date']).size()
z = pd.DataFrame(z)
z = z.rename(columns={0: "Count"})
z = z.reset_index()
# Sort within three groups
z = z.sort_values(by = ['Agency_Name','Merchant_Category','Transaction_Date'],ascending=True).reset_index(drop=True)

Then, we can use rolling function and mean function to calculate the past 30 days' average number of transactions for each transaction date.

In [62]:
z = z.set_index('Transaction_Date') # rolling function needs datetime index

# Calculate average number of transactions of past 30 days
z = z.groupby(['Agency_Name','Merchant_Category'])['Count'].rolling('30D').mean()
z = pd.DataFrame(z)

Now we calculate the average number of transactions of each cardholder in the past 30 days. The aggregation happens at cardholder's first name, last name, agency_name, merchant_category, and transaction_date level.

Section 4 Modeling ¶

Back to Table of Contents

Let’s use unsupervised KNN to detect outliers. The unsupervised k-NN method computes the Euclidean distance of an observation to other observations. The unsupervised KNN does not have any parameters to tune to make the performance better. It simply computes the distances to neighbors.

First, let's train our default KNN model with 'n_neighbors' =5. We don't want train the model every time we run this cell, so we write a if-else statement to save trained model as a pickle file.

With our trained KNN model, we can apply it to the test data and get the predictions and anomaly scores.

How is the “anomaly score” defined? Recall the k-NN model uses the Euclidean distance to measure the distance.

Since an outlier is the point that is distant from neighboring points, the outlier score is defined as the distance to its k-th nearest neighbor.

Each point will have an outlier score. Our job is to find those points with high outlier scores.

In [100]:
# Now we have the trained K-NN model, let's apply to the test data to get the predictions

print(dict(zip(unique, counts)))
# And you can generate the anomaly score using clf.decision_function:
y_test_scores = clf.decision_function(X_test)

From above, we can see 24303 data points are being classified as outliers.

Determine a reasonable boundary¶

A data point with a high anomaly score is abnormal. We can cut anomaly scores into percentile and use a histogram to find those points. The histogram below shows the count by the anomaly score percentile.

Most of the data points have low anomaly scores. The graph shows 95% data points have anomaly scores below 2.698.

If we choose 2.698 to be the cut point, we can suggest those >=2.698 to be outliers. Notice we use the anomaly scores of the training data to determine the boundary.

4.2 Aggregating Multiple Models ¶

Back to Table of Contents

However, many outlier detection algorithms tend to be very sensitive to outliers. In our case the unsupervised k-NN model can easily commit overfitting. We can aggregate mutiple models to produce a model with a stable outcome.

Here, we train five KNN models with different numbers of nearest neighbors.

In [126]:
from pyod.models.combination import aom, moa, average, maximization
from pyod.utils.utility import standardizer
# Standardize data
X_train = train
X_test =  test.iloc[:,0:15]

X_train_norm, X_test_norm = standardizer(X_train, X_test)
# Test a range of k-neighbors from 10 to 200. There will be 5 k-NN models.
n_clf = 5
k_list = [10,50,100,150,200]
# Just prepare data frames so we can store the model results
train_scores = np.zeros([X_train.shape[0], n_clf])
test_scores = np.zeros([X_test.shape[0], n_clf])
train_scores.shape
# Modeling
for i in range(n_clf):
    k = k_list[i]
    
    if os.path.exists('KNN_model_'+str(k)+'.pkl'):
        print('KNN Model with neighbors '+ str(k)+' exists, Loading model....')
        clf = pickle.load(open('KNN_model_'+str(k)+'.pkl', 'rb'))
        print("Done, model loaded. Now, calculating anomaly scores.")
        y_train_scores = clf.decision_scores_
        test_scores[:, i] = clf.decision_function(X_test_norm)
        
    else: 
        print("Missing model file, start training.....")    
        clf = KNN(n_neighbors=k, method='largest')
        clf.fit(X_train_norm)
        # Store the results in each column:
        train_scores[:, i] = clf.decision_scores_
        test_scores[:, i] = clf.decision_function(X_test_norm) 
        pickle.dump(clf, open('KNN_model_'+str(k)+'.pkl', 'wb')) # save trained models
# Decision scores have to be normalized before combination
train_scores_norm, test_scores_norm = standardizer(train_scores,test_scores)

All features in cluster 1 are larger than the features in cluster 0.
For example, cluster 1 has an agency merchant median ratio of 8.38. That is more than 4 times the ratio of cluster 0.

We have strong confidence in believing that cluster 1 is the anomaly group.

In this fraud detection project, we created 15 features from the raw transaction dataset. Then we used unsupervised learning to detect anomalies based on the prediction scores.

We trained a total of five models and used model combination techniques including average method, MOM, AOM, and MOA to prevent overfitting.

Our models can detect top percentile anomalies. These anomalies are validated by the difference between the normal and anomaly clusters.
